│ stop({"edit_points": [[7369, 7375,                                                     │
│ "llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp"]], "thoughts": "1. Understanding the │
│ Issue:\nThe crash is due to an assertion firing in                                     │
│ LoopVectorizationPlanner::computeBestVF that checks agreement between the VPlan cost   │
│ model and the legacy cost model: `(BestFactor.Width == LegacyVF.Width ||               │
│ planContainsAdditionalSimplifications(...))`. In the reproducer, the VPlan-based model │
│ selects a scalar VF (1), while the legacy cost model selects VF=2, and                 │
│ `planContainsAdditionalSimplifications` returns false, triggering the                  │
│ assertion.\n\nThe reproducer produces only a scalar VPlan candidate, and the VPlan     │
│ loop-vectorizer decides not to generate any vector instructions (`willGenerateVectors` │
│ is false). The legacy cost model still decides VF=2 is profitable, causing             │
│ disagreement.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\nThe debug log shows the assertion firing in  │
│ computeBestVF without detailed trace due to `--debug-only=` being empty, but the       │
│ debugger inspection reveals:\n- BestFactor.Width is scalar (1) with cost 4.\n-         │
│ LegacyVF.Width is 2 with cost 5.\n- VPlans contains a single plan with only scalar     │
│ VF.\nThus, VPlan didn’t consider any vector VF because it wouldn’t generate vectors,   │
│ whereas the legacy cost model still picked VF=2.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nThe       │
│ assertion assumes that when the two models disagree on VF, the VPlan contains          │
│ additional simplifications unaccounted by the legacy model. However, it does not       │
│ account for the case where VPlan legitimately only has a scalar VF (e.g., due to       │
│ `willGenerateVectors` returning false), while the legacy model still picks a vector    │
│ VF. In such situations, there is no actual transformation mismatch, since the VPlan    │
│ cannot generate vector code, and the disagreement is benign.\n\nTherefore, the         │
│ assertion is too strict: it must also allow the case when BestFactor is scalar or when │
│ the LegacyVF.Width is not among the available VFs in any VPlan. Otherwise, it          │
│ incorrectly fires on loops where vector code cannot be generated according to VPlan    │
│ rules.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s):\nModify the assertion block in computeBestVF to   │
│ relax the condition to avoid triggering the assertion when the best VPlan is scalar or │
│ when LegacyVF’s VF is not available in VPlans. Concretely, extend the condition to:\n- │
│ Skip asserting disagreement if `BestFactor.Width.isScalar()`; or\n- Skip asserting     │
│ disagreement if `!hasPlanWithVF(LegacyVF.Width)`.\n\nEdit at                           │
│ llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp lines 7369-7375:\nReplace the existing │
│ assert with a condition that checks these additional cases:\n\n```\n  // If the best   │
│ plan is scalar or the legacy-selected VF isn't available in any\n  // VPlan, don't     │
│ assert on disagreement: VPlan may legitimately refuse to\n  // generate vectors even   │
│ if the legacy model suggests doing so.\n  bool LegacyVFAvailable =                     │
│ hasPlanWithVF(LegacyVF.Width);\n  assert((BestFactor.Width == LegacyVF.Width ||        │
│ BestFactor.Width.isScalar() ||\n          !LegacyVFAvailable ||\n                      │
│ planContainsAdditionalSimplifications(getPlanFor(BestFactor.Width),\n                  │
│ CostCtx, OrigLoop)) &&\n         \" VPlan cost model and legacy cost model             │
│ disagreed\");\n```\nLeave the subsequent scalar-cost assertion unchanged.\n\nThis      │
│ change preserves the original intent of verifying disagreements only when both models  │
│ evaluated comparable vectorization options, and still asserts when the VPlan and       │
│ legacy cost model truly disagree without extra simplifications.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nBy  │
│ relaxing the assertion to also permit cases where only scalar VPlan exists or the      │
│ legacy-chosen VF is not present in any VPlan, we avoid false-positive assertion        │
│ failures when VPlan rightfully declines vectorization. This fixes the crash on the     │
│ provided reproducer without affecting transformation behavior and keeps the debug      │
│ check meaningful for actual disagreements."})                                          │
