│                                                                                        │
│ ### Root Cause Analysis ###                                                            │
│                                                                                        │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                                        │
│ 1. Understanding the Issue:                                                            │
│ The crash is due to an assertion firing in LoopVectorizationPlanner::computeBestVF     │
│ that checks agreement between the VPlan cost model and the legacy cost model:          │
│ `(BestFactor.Width == LegacyVF.Width || planContainsAdditionalSimplifications(...))`.  │
│ In the reproducer, the VPlan-based model selects a scalar VF (1), while the legacy     │
│ cost model selects VF=2, and `planContainsAdditionalSimplifications` returns false,    │
│ triggering the assertion.                                                              │
│                                                                                        │
│ The reproducer produces only a scalar VPlan candidate, and the VPlan loop-vectorizer   │
│ decides not to generate any vector instructions (`willGenerateVectors` is false). The  │
│ legacy cost model still decides VF=2 is profitable, causing disagreement.              │
│                                                                                        │
│ 2. Analyzing opt's Log:                                                                │
│ The debug log shows the assertion firing in computeBestVF without detailed trace due   │
│ to `--debug-only=` being empty, but the debugger inspection reveals:                   │
│ - BestFactor.Width is scalar (1) with cost 4.                                          │
│ - LegacyVF.Width is 2 with cost 5.                                                     │
│ - VPlans contains a single plan with only scalar VF.                                   │
│ Thus, VPlan didn’t consider any vector VF because it wouldn’t generate vectors,        │
│ whereas the legacy cost model still picked VF=2.                                       │
│                                                                                        │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis:                                                                │
│ The assertion assumes that when the two models disagree on VF, the VPlan contains      │
│ additional simplifications unaccounted by the legacy model. However, it does not       │
│ account for the case where VPlan legitimately only has a scalar VF (e.g., due to       │
│ `willGenerateVectors` returning false), while the legacy model still picks a vector    │
│ VF. In such situations, there is no actual transformation mismatch, since the VPlan    │
│ cannot generate vector code, and the disagreement is benign.                           │
│                                                                                        │
│ Therefore, the assertion is too strict: it must also allow the case when BestFactor is │
│ scalar or when the LegacyVF.Width is not among the available VFs in any VPlan.         │
│ Otherwise, it incorrectly fires on loops where vector code cannot be generated         │
│ according to VPlan rules.                                                              │
│                                                                                        │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Point(s):                                                             │
│ Modify the assertion block in computeBestVF to relax the condition to avoid triggering │
│ the assertion when the best VPlan is scalar or when LegacyVF’s VF is not available in  │
│ VPlans. Concretely, extend the condition to:                                           │
│ - Skip asserting disagreement if `BestFactor.Width.isScalar()`; or                     │
│ - Skip asserting disagreement if `!hasPlanWithVF(LegacyVF.Width)`.                     │
│                                                                                        │
│ Edit at llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp lines 7369-7375:               │
│ Replace the existing assert with a condition that checks these additional cases:       │
│                                                                                        │
│ ```                                                                                    │
│   // If the best plan is scalar or the legacy-selected VF isn't available in any       │
│   // VPlan, don't assert on disagreement: VPlan may legitimately refuse to             │
│   // generate vectors even if the legacy model suggests doing so.                      │
│   bool LegacyVFAvailable = hasPlanWithVF(LegacyVF.Width);                              │
│   assert((BestFactor.Width == LegacyVF.Width || BestFactor.Width.isScalar() ||         │
│           !LegacyVFAvailable ||                                                        │
│           planContainsAdditionalSimplifications(getPlanFor(BestFactor.Width),          │
│                                                CostCtx, OrigLoop)) &&                  │
│          " VPlan cost model and legacy cost model disagreed");                         │
│ ```                                                                                    │
│ Leave the subsequent scalar-cost assertion unchanged.                                  │
│                                                                                        │
│ This change preserves the original intent of verifying disagreements only when both    │
│ models evaluated comparable vectorization options, and still asserts when the VPlan    │
│ and legacy cost model truly disagree without extra simplifications.                    │
│                                                                                        │
│ 5. Conclusion:                                                                         │
│ By relaxing the assertion to also permit cases where only scalar VPlan exists or the   │
│ legacy-chosen VF is not present in any VPlan, we avoid false-positive assertion        │
│ failures when VPlan rightfully declines vectorization. This fixes the crash on the     │
│ provided reproducer without affecting transformation behavior and keeps the debug      │
│ check meaningful for actual disagreements.                                             │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------                                        │
│                                                                                        │
